Electrochemical impedance spectra (EIS) and photocurrent response were examined to study the separation and migration ability of photo-excited charges (Fig. 4
                        ). The diameter of semi-circle in the EIS Nyquist plots (Fig. 4a) represents the resistance of charge transfer (R
                        ct) at the solid/liquid interface [51]. Obviously, the CN/BW sample has a smaller Rct values than the individual CN and BW samples, revealing that the formation of heterostructure is favorable for improving the transport of photo-generated carriers and the charge transfer between catalyst and solution. Fig. 4b is the transient photocurrent responses of these CN, BW and CN/BW samples. The CN/BW sample shows the highest photocurrent response. It means the most efficient separation efficiency of photo-induced electrons and holes due to the sufficient charge transfer between the biphasic interface of CN and BW.
